<h4 style=3D"margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; line-height:115%"> <span s=
tyle=3D"font-family:'Amazon Ember'; font-weight:normal; font-variant:small-=
caps; letter-spacing:0.5pt">VPC/Subnet/Security Group Security</span> </h4>=
=20
<p style=3D"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size=
:9pt"> <span style=3D"font-family:'Amazon Ember'">VPC is a software defined=
 network that allows customers to create segmented or micro-segmented netwo=
rk domains to isolate traffic flow between different compute environments a=
nd AWS services as well as to join segments when needed in safe and limited=
 ways. VPCs can span multiple Availability Zones within a Region, but canno=
t span regions. AWS supports but IPv4 and IPv6 addresses.</span> </p>=20
<p style=3D"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size=
:9pt"> <span style=3D"font-family:'Amazon Ember'">The use of VPCs, Subnets =
and Security Groups will prevent lateral movement and connectivity within t=
he network unless it has been specifically provisioned. This creates micro-=
segmented networks.</span> </p>=20
<p style=3D"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size=
:9pt"> <span style=3D"font-family:'Amazon Ember'">Every packet flow on the =
network is individually authorized against a rule to validate the correct s=
ource and destination before it is transmitted and delivered. If a packet i=
s being routed to a destination without a rule that matches it, the packet =
is dropped. Reply addresses must be valid or the packet is dropped.</span> =
</p>=20
<p style=3D"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size=
:9pt"> <span style=3D"font-family:'Amazon Ember'">Address Resolution Protoc=
ol (ARP) packets trigger an authenticated database look-up, ARP packets are=
 not needed for discovery of the virtual network topology. This makes ARP s=
poofing highly improbable on the AWS network. </span> </p>=20
<p style=3D"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size=
:9pt"> <span style=3D"font-family:'Amazon Ember'">When provisioned VPCs do =
not have internet access, this must be provisioned using an Internet Gatewa=
y. Preventative, Detective and Responsive controls can be implemented stop =
an Internet Gateway being created, detect if one is present and if required=
 it can be deleted.</span> </p>=20
<p style=3D"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size=
:9pt"> <span style=3D"font-family:'Amazon Ember'; font-weight:bold">Subnets=
</span> </p>=20
<p style=3D"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size=
:9pt"> <span style=3D"font-family:'Amazon Ember'">The VPC will be subdivide=
d into multiple subnets which can either be Public with Public IPv4 address=
es or IPv6, allowing internet traffic if an Internet Gateway has been provi=
sioned in the VPC or Private using Private IPv4 addresses. Traffic between =
subnets can be restricted using Network Access Control Lists (ACLs) which p=
rovide a stateless firewall with ALLOW and DENY rules, to determine if traf=
fic is allowed in or out of the subnet. </span> </p>=20
<p style=3D"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size=
:9pt"> <span style=3D"font-family:'Amazon Ember'; font-weight:bold">&nbsp;<=
/span> </p>=20
<p style=3D"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size=
:9pt"> <span style=3D"font-family:'Amazon Ember'; font-weight:bold">Securit=
y Groups</span> </p>=20
<p style=3D"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size=
:9pt"> <span style=3D"font-family:'Amazon Ember'">Within each subnet resour=
ces use Security Groups which act as a stateful firewall that controls inbo=
und and outbound traffic to AWS resources. Resources which are launched int=
o the same Security Group will be able to pass network traffic, for example=
 where EC2 instance are part of an autoscaling group, but would need rules =
to allow inbound traffic from another AWS resource or the internet (if in a=
 subnet which allows Internet Traffic) and outbound rules to reach other AW=
S resources or the internet. Rules specify the Protocol, Port Range and sou=
rce/destination which can be specified as either CIDR or another Security G=
roup. </span> </p>=20
<p style=3D"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size=
:9pt"> <span style=3D"font-family:'Amazon Ember'; font-weight:bold">NAT Gat=
eway</span> </p>=20
<p style=3D"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size=
:9pt"> <span style=3D"font-family:'Amazon Ember'">VPC resources in private =
subnets which require outbound internet connectivity will use a Network Add=
ress Translation (NAT) gateway in a public subnet. This enables outbound tr=
affic to be initiated, but prevents inbound traffic from reaching hosts in =
a private subnet. For example, if a host in the private subnet requires pat=
ching</span> </p>=20
